You add it to a noun
to turn it into possessive form.

91
00:05:40,139 --> 00:05:42,141
In other words, the wound on their necks

92
00:05:43,076 --> 00:05:47,880
could be the murderer's claim that
the victims were his possessions.

93
00:05:50,183 --> 00:05:53,853
But this alone can't even
be circumstantial evidence.

94
00:05:57,657 --> 00:06:00,660
So you have never met KooZ?

95
00:06:01,194 --> 00:06:05,531
No. He sent me a follow request,
so I accepted it. That's all.

96
00:06:06,532 --> 00:06:09,369
Could the person be the murderer?

97
00:06:09,435 --> 00:06:10,636
JUNPEI FUJITA, DEFENDANT

98
00:06:10,703 --> 00:06:12,038
We have to investigate.

99
00:06:14,707 --> 00:06:17,377
The person arrested
in the murder 11 years ago

100
00:06:18,144 --> 00:06:21,848
killed himself
after he lost the case, didn't he?

101
00:06:24,584 --> 00:06:25,485
Yes.

102
00:06:29,455 --> 00:06:31,224
I know how he felt!

103
00:06:32,325 --> 00:06:34,694
He was arrested
for something he didn't do,

104
00:06:35,261 --> 00:06:37,430
so he would rather die in that case!

105
00:06:37,497 --> 00:06:38,598
Mr. Fujita!

106
00:06:41,467 --> 00:06:42,535
Please don't give up.

107
00:06:45,138 --> 00:06:46,806
Until the very last moment…

108
00:06:48,441 --> 00:06:50,643
I'm going to go all out
to investigate and defend you.

109
00:06:51,644 --> 00:06:54,046
TODOROKI POLICE STATION

110
00:06:54,714 --> 00:06:56,182
Excuse me.

111
00:06:56,783 --> 00:06:57,617
Yes?

112
00:06:58,518 --> 00:07:01,387
I'm here to turn myself in to the police.

113
00:07:02,288 --> 00:07:04,157
Last night, I stabbed someone.

114
00:07:09,228 --> 00:07:09,962
MIC GENERAL LEGAL OFFICES
KIYOSHI DOGO

115
00:07:10,029 --> 00:07:11,264
Impressive.

116
00:07:11,330 --> 00:07:13,900
The guy turned himself in
and he's here to negotiate already.

117
00:07:13,966 --> 00:07:15,668
If the negotiation is successful,

118
00:07:15,735 --> 00:07:17,303
it'll give him an advantage in the trial.

119
00:07:17,870 --> 00:07:20,072
He said he was sorry about
what he did to Miss Wakura

120
00:07:20,139 --> 00:07:21,541
and he regrets doing it.

121
00:07:21,607 --> 00:07:24,477
He did not plan the assault,

122
00:07:24,544 --> 00:07:26,712
he just did it on impulse.

123
00:07:26,779 --> 00:07:29,449
In other words,
the victim could have been anyone?

124
00:07:29,515 --> 00:07:33,986
Yes. He got frightened after that
and turned himself in to the police.

125
00:07:36,122 --> 00:07:39,358
This is my client's personal details.

126
00:07:39,425 --> 00:07:42,094
I have his permission.

127
00:07:42,161 --> 00:07:43,563
"Kazunari Kozu."

128
00:07:43,629 --> 00:07:44,464
NAME: KAZUNARI KOZU

129
00:07:45,498 --> 00:07:46,899
Kozu?

130
00:07:46,966 --> 00:07:47,967
OCCUPATION: EMPLOYEE
AT UNIVERSITY STUDENT AFFAIRS OFFICE

131
00:07:48,034 --> 00:07:50,603
It says he works at
a university's student affairs office.

132
00:07:50,670 --> 00:07:51,771
Which university is it?

133
00:07:51,838 --> 00:07:54,440
I heard that it is Seiran Arts University.

134
00:07:56,008 --> 00:07:56,843
Excuse me.

135
00:08:04,717 --> 00:08:06,719
"Seiran Arts University."

136
00:08:06,786 --> 00:08:07,820
Mr. Kurokawa.

137
00:08:08,888 --> 00:08:11,858
Does the name Kozu ring a bell?

138
00:08:11,924 --> 00:08:12,959
KOOZ: TOTAL NO. OF MURDERS IN 2017, 20,598

139
00:08:14,327 --> 00:08:18,331
My client's father is now retired,

140
00:08:18,397 --> 00:08:21,200
but he is a renowned pathologist.

141
00:08:21,267 --> 00:08:22,735
He will pay more to settle this--

142
00:08:22,802 --> 00:08:25,338
We'll talk to Wakura whether
we'll settle it out of court or not,

143
00:08:27,039 --> 00:08:28,508
but on one condition.

144
00:08:29,842 --> 00:08:31,244
Condition?

145
00:08:31,944 --> 00:08:34,113
NAME: KAZUNARI KOZU

146
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:39,785
I am going to interview this man.

147
00:08:44,824 --> 00:08:46,759
TODOROKI POLICE STATION

148
00:08:48,561 --> 00:08:50,830
You were actually going to stab me,
weren't you?

149
00:08:50,897 --> 00:08:53,266
KAZUNARI KOZU, SUSPECT

150
00:08:53,332 --> 00:08:54,433
Well…

151
00:08:55,101 --> 00:08:58,804
I saw you on the news.
You're a famous lawyer, right?

152
00:08:59,472 --> 00:09:00,606
No.

153
00:09:00,673 --> 00:09:03,109
Clearing someone of false charges
must be difficult.

154
00:09:04,744 --> 00:09:05,711
The police

155
00:09:05,778 --> 00:09:10,182
leaps at someone's self-confession
or simple circumstantial evidence.

156
00:09:11,684 --> 00:09:14,053
You work at a university's
student affairs office?

157
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:15,922
My father got me the job.

158
00:09:15,988 --> 00:09:19,692
I had been idling about at this age.
It's been half a year,

159
00:09:20,226 --> 00:09:22,295
but I couldn't fit in at work.

160
00:09:23,329 --> 00:09:24,163
Half a year?

161
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:26,732
I had been living abroad
for nearly ten years,

162
00:09:26,799 --> 00:09:29,835
so my dad said it was time
for me to re-join society.

163
00:09:29,902 --> 00:09:33,272
But I ended up working at
the student affairs office again.

164
00:09:35,107 --> 00:09:37,076
You had worked at
the student affairs office before?

165
00:09:37,743 --> 00:09:39,679
Yes, at Touo University.

166
00:09:40,913 --> 00:09:43,316
It made me feel inferior.

167
00:09:43,382 --> 00:09:47,954
All the students were gifted
and enjoying their youth.

168
00:09:48,588 --> 00:09:52,024
It annoyed me so much at that time.

169
00:09:53,759 --> 00:09:55,394
But you know,

170
00:09:56,329 --> 00:09:59,432
no matter how gifted they are
and how much they enjoy their youth,

171
00:09:59,498 --> 00:10:01,968
when people die,
they die in no time at all.

172
00:10:04,937 --> 00:10:06,072
You…

173
00:10:12,478 --> 00:10:13,579
Actually…

174
00:10:15,481 --> 00:10:17,583
I killed all three of them.

175
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:23,422
In the case 11 years ago
and the two lately.

176
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:27,093
When I stabbed the knife into
their necks and twisted it,

177
00:10:27,159 --> 00:10:28,794
it was so satisfying!

178
00:10:36,068 --> 00:10:36,969
What's the matter?

179
00:10:37,036 --> 00:10:39,171
The lawyer suddenly…

180
00:10:39,238 --> 00:10:42,041
He is the murderer! He just confessed it.

181
00:10:42,108 --> 00:10:43,643
I didn't say that.

182
00:10:43,709 --> 00:10:46,245
The public didn't know
about the wound on their necks!

183
00:10:46,879 --> 00:10:50,082
He knows that because he is
the murderer, without a doubt!

184
00:10:50,149 --> 00:10:52,084
-What are you talking about?
-Calm down.

185
00:10:53,019 --> 00:10:53,953
The interview is over.

186
00:10:54,920 --> 00:10:58,391
You treat me like a murderer
without any evidence.

187
00:10:58,457 --> 00:11:00,826
Are you a detective who forces people
to make a confession?

188
00:11:10,836 --> 00:11:13,172
Mr. Kurokawa, how did the interview go?

189
00:11:13,239 --> 00:11:14,407
Kurokawa.

190
00:11:17,476 --> 00:11:18,911
Mr. Kurokawa, what's the matter?

191
00:11:18,978 --> 00:11:20,479
Hey, don't ignore us!

192
00:11:20,546 --> 00:11:21,747
Kurokawa.

193
00:11:21,814 --> 00:11:23,282
He confessed it.

194
00:11:26,185 --> 00:11:30,056
He said to me
that he killed all three of them.

195
00:11:40,099 --> 00:11:42,101
Mr. Kurokawa. Breathe in.

196
00:11:43,002 --> 00:11:45,337
Take a deep breath. Slowly.

197
00:11:48,507 --> 00:11:49,442
I'm sorry.

198
00:11:53,112 --> 00:11:54,680
But I have no evidence!

199
00:11:54,747 --> 00:11:59,085
Evidence… None was found
in those two murders too.

200
00:11:59,151 --> 00:12:02,455
It must be even harder
to get the evidence 11 years ago.

201
00:12:04,123 --> 00:12:05,524
The investigator at that time.

202
00:12:06,092 --> 00:12:08,227
Do you have any clue who it was?

203
00:12:08,794 --> 00:12:12,465
When I produced the documentary,
one person was evasive.

204
00:12:12,965 --> 00:12:15,134
He was still active at that time,
so he refused to be interviewed,

205
00:12:16,001 --> 00:12:17,470
but he should be retired now.

206
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:26,445
Are you bringing up the murder
11 years ago again?

207
00:12:27,580 --> 00:12:31,117
We heard that you participated in
the initial investigation,

208
00:12:31,183 --> 00:12:33,319
so we hope you'll tell us about it.

209
00:12:33,385 --> 00:12:36,055
At that time, in Kanagawa,

210
00:12:36,122 --> 00:12:38,824
there was another major case, right?

211
00:12:40,960 --> 00:12:42,895
A family in Hodogaya was murdered.

212
00:12:42,962 --> 00:12:44,997
A man arrested by the police
wasn't charged

213
00:12:45,064 --> 00:12:47,500
by Yokohama Prosecutors Office
due to lack of evidence.

214
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:50,636
The man committed the murder
right after that, right?

215
00:12:51,303 --> 00:12:54,073
-It was…
-A family of five was brutally murdered.

216
00:12:54,840 --> 00:12:57,443
The prosecutors' office's
stupid young prosecutor

217
00:12:58,144 --> 00:13:00,546
caused the death of people
who didn't have to die.

218
00:13:01,714 --> 00:13:04,183
The Touo University Student
Murder Case happened that instant.

219
00:13:06,886 --> 00:13:08,954
To regain people's trust,

220
00:13:10,089 --> 00:13:12,925
the police wanted to solve the case
at an early stage, right?

221
00:13:13,425 --> 00:13:14,293
So they rushed it--

222
00:13:14,360 --> 00:13:16,328
We made no mistake in our investigation.

223
00:13:17,363 --> 00:13:18,864
We, the police,

224
00:13:19,732 --> 00:13:24,036
arrested the most likely suspect
and collected evidence.

225
00:13:24,103 --> 00:13:27,740
The method was the most proper one
in an investigation.

226
00:13:27,807 --> 00:13:29,408
We want to pick up the pieces,

227
00:13:29,909 --> 00:13:33,112
starting from that juncture.

228
00:13:34,146 --> 00:13:35,915
If in the case 11 years ago,

229
00:13:36,649 --> 00:13:38,551
something wasn't used as evidence,

230
00:13:38,617 --> 00:13:41,453
another truth could be hidden in it.

231
00:13:42,521 --> 00:13:44,557
Please tell us anything you know.

232
00:13:45,357 --> 00:13:47,793
-Please help us.
-Please help us.

233
00:13:52,398 --> 00:13:53,933
A cigarette butt?

234
00:13:53,999 --> 00:13:56,302
It was found at the crime scene,

235
00:13:56,368 --> 00:14:01,173
but it wasn't even presented
as evidence at the trial at that time

236
00:14:01,240 --> 00:14:03,475
because Senior Asama didn't smoke.

237
00:14:04,109 --> 00:14:07,146
The prosecutor can choose
what they present as evidence, right?

238
00:14:07,780 --> 00:14:11,517
That's why they didn't present
anything unfavorable to them.

239
00:14:11,584 --> 00:14:13,953
If we analyze the cigarette butt,

240
00:14:14,019 --> 00:14:16,789
maybe we can prove that Kozu was involved.

241
00:14:18,190 --> 00:14:19,325
I'll file an appeal

242
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:21,627
in Yokohama District Court
for the retrial of the case 11 years ago

243
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:23,863
and request for the disclosure
of the cigarette butt collected.

